    {
      "title": "Figures of speech in passages",
      "html": "<p>Writers use figurative language to make ideas vivid. Common figures include:</p>\n  <ul><li><b>Simile</b> — comparison with <i>as / like</i>: <i>brave as a lion</i>.</li>\n  <li><b>Metaphor</b> — direct comparison: <i>Time is a thief</i>.</li>\n  <li><b>Personification</b> — giving human qualities to things: <i>the sun smiled</i>.</li>\n  <li><b>Hyperbole</b> — exaggeration for effect: <i>I've told you a million times</i>.</li>\n  <li><b>Litotes</b> — understatement: <i>not bad</i> (= very good).</li>\n  <li><b>Oxymoron</b> — apparent contradiction: <i>deafening silence</i>.</li>\n  <li><b>Alliteration</b> — repeated initial sounds: <i>slippery snakes</i>.</li>\n  <li><b>Onomatopoeia</b> — words that imitate sounds: <i>buzz, clang, hiss</i>.</li>\n  <li><b>Irony</b> — meaning opposite of the literal: <i>a fire station burnt down</i> (situational).</li>\n  <li><b>Euphemism</b> — mild expression: <i>passed away</i> (= died).</li></ul>",
      "examples": [
        {
          "q": "Identify the figure: <i>The waves danced along the shore.</i>",
          "a": "Personification — waves given the human action of dancing."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Drawing inferences",
      "html": "<p>An <b>inference</b> is a reasonable conclusion drawn from what a passage says, not stated directly.</p>\n  <p>Ask: <i>What does the writer expect me to understand without saying it aloud?</i></p>\n  <p>Steps:</p>\n  <ol><li>Note the exact words and details in the passage.</li>\n  <li>Combine those details with common knowledge.</li>\n  <li>Choose the option that fits the passage evidence — not just your feelings.</li></ol>\n  <p>Beware of over-inferring: any conclusion must be justified by something the writer wrote.</p>",
      "examples": [
        {
          "q": "From <i>Ada glanced at her watch and quickened her pace</i>, what can you infer?",
          "a": "That Ada was afraid of being late."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Summary of an argumentative passage",
      "html": "<p>An <b>argumentative passage</b> puts forward a case with reasons. Its summary must list those <b>reasons</b>, not merely restate the topic.</p>\n  <h4>Bullet-point method</h4>\n  <ol><li>State the writer's main claim in one sentence.</li>\n  <li>List each reason or piece of evidence as one bullet — in your own words.</li>\n  <li>Answer only the number of points asked (say, four reasons).</li>\n  <li>Keep to the word limit.</li></ol>",
      "examples": [
        {
          "q": "If asked for <i>four reasons the writer opposes plastic bags</i>, what should you list?",
          "a": "Four separate, non-overlapping reasons, each rephrased in your own words and drawn only from the passage."
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
